# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mining-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] In order to gain more control over their operations, mining companies may implement mining automation software or processes.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Reports generated by mine automation software allow administrators to identify productivity bottlenecks, increase accountability, and better understand return on investment.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Addressing concerns about how to improve productivity and safety in the mine site, some mine companies are turning to equipment automation consisting of robotic hardware and software technologies that convert vehicles or equipment into autonomous mining units.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Mine equipment automation comes in four different forms: remote control, teleoperation, driver assist, and full automation.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Remote control mining equipment usually refers to mining vehicles such as excavators or bulldozers that are controlled with a handheld remote control.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] An operator stands in line-of-sight and uses the remote control to perform the normal vehicle functions.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Because visibility and feel of the machine are heavily reduced, vehicle productivity is generally reduced as well using remote control.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Remote control technology is generally used to enable mining equipment to operate in dangerous conditions such as unstable terrain, blast areas or in high risk areas of falling debris, or underground mining.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Remote control technology is generally the least expensive way to automate mining equipment making it an ideal entry point for companies looking to test the viability of robotic technology in their mine.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Teleoperated mining equipment refers to mining vehicles that are controlled by an operator at a remote location with the use of cameras, sensors, and possibly additional positioning software.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Teleoperation allows an operator to further remove themselves from the mining location and control a vehicle from a more protected environment.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Joysticks or other handheld controls are still used to control the vehicle's functions, and operators have greater access to vehicle telemetry and positioning data through the teleoperation software.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] With the operator removed from the cab, teleoperated mining vehicles may also experience reduced productivity; however, the operator has a better vantage point than remote control from on-vehicle cameras and sensors and is further removed from potentially dangerous conditions.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] "Driver assist" refers to partly automated control of mining machines.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Only some of the functions are automated and operator intervention is needed.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Common functions include both spotting assist and collision avoidance systems.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] "Full automation" can refer to the autonomous control of one or more mining vehicles.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Robotic components manage all critical vehicle functions including ignition, steering, transmission, acceleration, braking, and implement control (i.e. blade control, dump bed control, excavator bucket and boom, etc.) without the need for operator intervention.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Fully autonomous mining systems experience the most productivity gains as software controls one or more mining vehicles allowing operators to take on the role of mining facilitators, troubleshooting errors and monitoring efficiency.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] The benefits of mining equipment automation technologies are varied but may include: improved safety, better fuel efficiency, increased productivity, reduced unscheduled maintenance, improved working conditions, better vehicle utilization, and reduced driver fatigue and attrition.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Automation technologies are an efficient way to mitigate the effects of widespread labor shortages for positions such as haul truck driver.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] In the face of falling commodity prices, many mining companies are looking for ways to dramatically reduce overhead costs while still maintaining site safety and integrity; automation may be the answer.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Critics of vehicle automation often focus on the potential for robotic technology to eliminate jobs while proponents counter that while some jobs will become obsolete (normally the dirty, dangerous, or monotonous jobs), others will be created.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Communities supporting underprivileged workers that rely on entry level mining positions are worried about and are calling for social responsibility as mining companies transition to automation technologies that promise to increase productivity in the face of falling commodity prices.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Risk averse mining companies are also reluctant to commit large amounts of capital to an unproven technology, preferring more often to enter the automation scene at lower, more inexpensive levels such as remote control.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Rio Tinto Group embarked on their Mine of the Future initiative in 2008.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] From a control center in Perth, Rio Tinto employees operate autonomous mining equipment in Australia's remote but mineral rich Pilbara region.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] The autonomous mining vehicles reduce the footprint of the mining giant while improving productivity and vehicle utilization.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] As of June 2014, Rio Tinto's autonomous mining fleet reached the milestone of 200 million tonnes hauled.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Rio Tinto also operate a number of autonomous blast hole drill rigs.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Located near Salt Lake City, Utah, the Bingham Canyon Mine (Kennecott Utah Copper/Rio Tinto) is one of the largest open pit mines in the world and one of the world's largest copper producers.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] In April 2013, the mine experienced a catastrophic landslide that halted much of the mine's operations.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] As part of the cleanup efforts and to improve safety, mine administrators turned to remote control excavator, dozers and teleremote blast hole drills to perform work on the highly unstable terrain areas.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Robotic technology helped Kennecott to reduce the steeper, more dangerous areas of the slide to allow manned vehicles access for cleanup efforts.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] German company EEP Elektro-Elektronik Pranjic delivered and put into operation more than 60 sets of advanced automatic control for underground coal mining for the period ~ 2006–2016.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] For the first time completely deserted coal mining technology has been used by the Chinese concern «China National Coal Group Corp.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] (CME)» at the mine «Tang Shan Gou» (longwall mining, shearers, three lava, depth 200 m), and at the mine «Nan Liang» (one plow, depth 100 m).
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Both coal mines have coal layer thickness 1–1.7 m.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Monitoring the harvesting is carried out by means of video cameras (in real time with signal transmission over optical fiber).
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Typically, an underground staff is required to monitor the production process and for carrying out repairs.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] Automation has improved the safety and economic performance.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] BHP have deployed a number of autonomous mining components as part of their Next Generation Mining program.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] This includes autonomous drills and autonomous trucks in the Pilbara region.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] In March 2021, Ferrexpo plc announced that it had successfully deployed the first large scale autonomous mining trucks in Europe with the conversion of its CAT 793D haul trucks.
[src:mining-automation/automated-mining] The company has used semi-autonomous drill rigs at its operations since 2017.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] A **drilling rig** is an integrated system that drills wells, such as oil or water wells, or holes for piling and other construction purposes, into the earth's subsurface.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Drilling rigs can be massive structures housing equipment used to drill water wells, oil wells, or natural gas extraction wells, or they can be small enough to be moved manually by one person and such are called augers.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Drilling rigs can sample subsurface mineral deposits, test rock, soil and groundwater physical properties, and also can be used to install sub-surface fabrications, such as underground utilities, instrumentation, tunnels or wells.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Drilling rigs can be mobile equipment mounted on trucks, tracks or trailers, or more permanent land or marine-based structures (such as oil platforms, commonly called 'offshore oil rigs' even if they don't contain a drilling rig).
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The term "rig" therefore generally refers to the complex equipment that is used to penetrate the surface of the Earth's crust.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Small to medium-sized drilling rigs are mobile, such as those used in mineral exploration drilling, blast-hole, water wells and environmental investigations.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Larger rigs are capable of drilling through thousands of metres of the Earth's crust, using large "mud pumps" to circulate drilling fluid (slurry) through the bit and up the casing annulus, for cooling and removing the "cuttings" while a well is drilled.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Hoists in the rig, a derrick, can lift hundreds of tons of pipe.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Other equipment can force acid or sand into reservoirs to facilitate extraction of the oil or natural gas; and in remote locations there can be permanent living accommodation and catering for crews (which may be more than a hundred).
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Marine rigs may operate thousands of miles distant from the supply base with infrequent crew rotation or cycle.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Until internal combustion engines were developed in the late 19th century, the main method for drilling rock was muscle power of man or animal.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The technique of oil drilling through percussion or rotary drilling has its origins dating back to the ancient Chinese Han dynasty in 100 BC, where percussion drilling was used to extract natural gas in the Sichuan province.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Early oil and gas drilling methods were seemingly primitive although the process required several technical skills.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The skills involved the availability of heavy iron bits and long bamboo poles, the manufacturing of long and sturdy cables woven from bamboo fiber, and levers.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Heavy iron bits were attached to long bamboo cables suspended from bamboo derricks and then were repeatedly raised and dropped into a manually dug hole by having two to six men jumping on a lever.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Han dynasty oil wells made by percussion drilling were effective but only reached 10 meters deep and 100 meters by the 10th century.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] By the 16th century, the Chinese were exploring and drilling oil wells more than 2,000 feet (610 m) deep.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Chinese well drilling technology was introduced to Europe in 1828.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] A modernized variant of the ancient Chinese drilling technique was used by American businessman Edwin Drake to drill Pennsylvania's first oil well in 1859 using small steam engines to power the drilling process rather than by human muscle.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Cable tool drilling was developed in ancient China and was used for drilling brine wells.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The salt domes also held natural gas, which some wells produced and which was used for evaporation of the brine.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Drake learned of cable tool drilling from Chinese laborers in the U.S.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The first primary product was kerosene for lamps and heaters.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Similar developments around Baku fed the European market.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] In the 1970s, outside of the oil and gas industry, roller bits using mud circulation were replaced by the first pneumatic reciprocating piston Reverse Circulation (RC) drills.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The former became essentially obsolete for most shallow drilling, now only used in certain situations where rocks preclude other methods.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] RC drilling proved much faster and more efficient.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] It continues to improve with better metallurgy, deriving harder, more durable bits and new compressors capable of delivering higher air pressures at higher volumes, enabling deeper and faster penetration.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Diamond drilling has remained essentially unchanged since its inception.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Oil and natural gas drilling rigs are used not only to identify geologic reservoirs, but also used to create holes that allow the extraction of oil or natural gas from those reservoirs.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Primarily in onshore oil and gas fields once a well has been drilled, the drilling rig will be moved off of the well and a service rig (a smaller rig) that is purpose-built for completions will be moved on to the well to get the well on line.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] This frees up the drilling rig to drill another hole and streamlines the operation as well as allowing for specialization of certain services, i.e. completions vs. drilling.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Mining drilling rigs are used for two main purposes, exploration drilling which aims to identify the location and quality of a mineral, and production drilling, used in the production-cycle for mining.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Drilling rigs used for rock blasting for surface mines vary in size dependent on the size of the hole desired, and is typically classified into smaller pre-split and larger production holes.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Underground mining (hard rock) uses a variety of drill rigs dependent on the desired purpose, such as production, bolting, cabling, and tunnelling.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] In early oil exploration, drilling rigs were semi-permanent in nature and the derricks were often built on site and left in place after the completion of the well.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] In more recent times drilling rigs are expensive custom-built machines that can be moved from well to well.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Some light duty drilling rigs are like a mobile crane and are more usually used to drill water wells.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Larger land rigs must be broken apart into sections and loads to move to a new place, a process which can often take weeks.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Small mobile drilling rigs are also used to drill or bore piles.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Rigs can range from 100 short tons (91,000 kg) continuous flight auger (CFA) rigs to small air powered rigs used to drill holes in quarries, etc.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] These rigs use the same technology and equipment as the oil drilling rigs, just on a smaller scale.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The drilling mechanisms outlined below differ mechanically in terms of the machinery used, but also in terms of the method by which drill cuttings are removed from the cutting face of the drill and returned to surface.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] An automated drill rig (ADR) is an automated full-sized walking land-based drill rig that drills long lateral sections in horizontal wells for the oil and gas industry.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] ADRs are agile rigs that can move from pad to pad to new well sites faster than other full-sized drilling rigs.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] ADR is used extensively in the Athabasca oil sands.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] 118, for steam assisted gravity drainage (SAGD) applications was mobilized by Deer Creek Energy Limited, a Calgary-based oilsands company.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Its main function is the drilling of holes in the ground and other materials - or surfaces such as ice, wood, etc.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The design of an auger depends on the kind of material it's meant to drill into, hence there are different types of auger drills.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Auger drills come in varying sizes and can drill holes up to a depth of 95 feet below the ground.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] They are known to be quite versatile, saving time and energy during construction work or even personal projects.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The auger is a helical screw made of steel casing with curved flights that rotates as it's pushed into the ground by a drill head.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] As the auger rotates, it brings excavated material to the surface, which helps keep the borehole open and prevents it from collapsing.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Augers can be mounted on trucks or other machines and come in different lengths and diameters.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Auger drilling is used in many fields, including construction, environmental studies, and geotechnical investigations.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] There are different auger drilling methods, including hand auger drilling and hollow stem auger drilling.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Hand auger drilling is a cost-effective method that's often used in areas with shallow soil, but it can be time-consuming and labor-intensive.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Hollow stem auger drilling uses a large, hollow auger that removes soil as it drills.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Auger drilling is often quieter and less vibration-prone than other drilling methods, like drive drilling, so it can also be used in urban areas.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] When using an auger, it's important to take safety precautions, such as wearing protective equipment like gloves, eye and ear protectors, and closed-toe boots.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] You should also make sure the auger and attachments are secure, engage the drill's high torque gear, and start drilling slowly.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] A drill bucket, or auger bucket, is a drilling head that accumulates spoil inside and can be lifted from the hole periodically to be emptied.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] This method is particularly effective for drilling through hard and compacted soils, as well as rocks, due to the bucket's cylindrical design with cutting teeth at the base, which excavates and retains soil or rock as it rotates.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Drill buckets are commonly used in foundation drilling for constructing deep piles and shafts.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] They come in various sizes and configurations, tailored to specific ground conditions and project requirements, and can be equipped with wear-resistant components to enhance durability in abrasive environments.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Additionally, modern drill buckets may include a vented bottom to release trapped air and facilitate faster spoil removal.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The International Association of Drilling Contractors (IADC) is the global trade association representing the drilling industry.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] Founded in 1940 and headquartered in Houston, Texas, the IADC represents drilling contractors, oil and gas operators, and service companies across more than 50 countries.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The IADC publishes *Drilling Contractor*, the industry's primary technical magazine covering drilling technology, operations, and safety practices.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] The International Association of Oil and Gas Producers (IOGP) is a global industry association representing oil and gas companies and national associations.
[src:mining-automation/drilling-rig] IOGP collaborates with drilling contractors and service companies to develop industry-wide safety standards, recommended practices, and incident reporting frameworks for upstream operations.
[src:mining-automation/haul-truck] Most haul trucks have a two-axle design, but two well-known models from the 1970s, the 350T Terex Titan and 235T WABCO 3200/B, had three axles.
[src:mining-automation/haul-truck] Haul truck capacities range from 40 short tons (36.3 t; 35.7 long tons) to nearly 500 short tons (454 t; 446 long tons).
[src:mining-automation/haul-truck] An example on the smaller end is the Caterpillar 775 (rated at 70 short tons [62 long tons]).
[src:mining-automation/haul-truck] Quarry operations (which produce payloads that have value) typically employ smaller trucks than mining operations (such as removing undesirable overburden, an expense).
[src:mining-automation/haul-truck] Most large haul trucks use some form of traction motors coupled to regenerative braking for power, braking, or both.
[src:mining-automation/haul-truck] The largest haul trucks, with a payload capacity of 300 short tons (270 long tons) or greater, are referred to as *ultra class* trucks.
[src:mining-automation/haul-truck] As of 2025, the BelAZ 75710 is the truck with the highest payload capacity, 450 metric tons (440 long tons; 500 short tons).
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] A **loader** is a heavy equipment machine used in construction to move or load materials such as soil, rock, sand, demolition debris, etc. into or onto another type of machinery (such as a dump truck, conveyor belt, feed-hopper, or railroad car).
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] There are many types of loader, which, depending on design and application, are variously called a **bucket loader**, **end loader**, **front loader**, **front-end loader**, **payloader**, **high lift**, **scoop**, **shovel dozer**, **skid-steer**, **tractor loader** or **wheel loader**.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] A loader is commonly used to move a stockpiled material from ground level and deposit it into an awaiting dump truck or into an open trench excavation.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The loader assembly may be a removable attachment or permanently mounted.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Often the bucket can be replaced with other devices or tools—for example, many can mount forks to lift heavy pallets or shipping containers, and a hydraulically opening "clamshell" bucket allows a loader to act as a light dozer or scraper.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The bucket can also be augmented with devices like a bale grappler for handling large bales of hay or straw.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Small loaders, such as the GEHL or Manitou Skid Steer are suitable to work inside buildings and on high floors.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Sometimes, construction happens inside a building or many floors above the ground.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Because GEHL or Manitou skid steer loaders have a compact size and are not too heavy, a crane can lift them onto the top floor of a new building.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Other companies like CASE in America and Whitlock in the UK had been manufacturing excavator loaders well before JCB.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The largest loader in the world is LeTourneau L-2350.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Currently these large loaders are in production in the Longview, Texas facility.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The L-2350 uses a diesel-electric propulsion system similar to that used in a locomotive.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Each rubber tired wheel is driven by its own independent electric motor.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Loaders are used mainly for loading materials into trucks, laying pipe, clearing rubble, and digging.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] A loader is not the most efficient machine for digging as it cannot dig very deep below the level of its wheels, like a backhoe or an excavator can.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The capacity of a loader bucket can be anywhere from 0.5 to 36 m3 depending upon the size of the machine and its application.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The front loader's bucket capacity is generally much bigger than a bucket capacity of a backhoe loader.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Unlike most bulldozers, most loaders are wheeled and not tracked, although track loaders are common.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] They are successful where sharp-edged materials in construction debris would damage rubber wheels, or where the ground is soft and muddy.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Wheels provide better mobility and speed and do not damage paved roads as much as tracks, but provide less traction.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] In construction areas loaders are also used to transport building materials such as bricks, pipe, metal bars, and digging tools over short distances.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Front-loaders are commonly used to remove snow especially from sidewalks, parking lots, and other areas too small for using snowplows and other heavy equipment.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] They are sometimes used as snowplows with a snowplow attachment but commonly have a bucket or snow basket, which can also be used to load snow into the rear compartment of a snowplow or dump truck.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] High-tip buckets are suitable for light materials such as chip, peat and light gravel and when the bucket is emptied from a height.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Unlike backhoes or standard tractors fitted with a front bucket, many large loaders do not use automotive steering mechanisms.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Instead, they steer by a hydraulically actuated pivot point set exactly between the front and rear axles.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] This is referred to as "articulated steering" and allows the front axle to be solid, allowing it to carry greater weight.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Articulated steering provides better maneuverability for a given wheelbase.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Since the front wheels and attachment rotate on the same axis, the operator is able to "steer" his load in an arc after positioning the machine, which can be useful.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The tradeoff is that when the machine is "twisted" to one side and a heavy load is lifted high, it has a greater risk of turning over to the "wide" side.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Front loaders gained popularity during the last two decades, especially in urban engineering projects and small earthmoving works.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Heavy equipment manufacturers offer a wide range of loader sizes and duties.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The term "loader" is also used in the debris removal field to describe the boom on a grapple truck.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The major components included in a loader are the engine (diesel in almost all cases), the hydraulic components (such as pumps, motors and valves) and the transmission components (gearbox, axles, wheels/tracks, pumps, motors, etc.).
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The engine runs both the hydraulics and the transmission, and these in turn move the front attachment (a bucket, forks, sweeper, etc.) to manipulate the material being handled, and the wheels or tracks to move the machine around the jobsite.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The first wheel loader was invented by Frank G.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Hough in 1939, it was called the Payloader.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] This machine consisted of a vertical mast affixed to the front of a tractor with a pair of loader arms running from the back of the machine ending in a forwards bucket, with the main lifting mechanism being driven a cable tensioned via vertically lifting hydraulic cylinder located inside the mast.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Today wheel loaders are articulated, a design choice introduced in 1953 via Mixermobile's Scoopmobile series of wheel loaders.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] This articulation allows them both a superior turning radius and the ability to move the bucket in a small horizontal arc without having to move forward like a conventionally steering chassis.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The Israeli Combat Engineering Corps uses armored wheel loaders for construction and combat engineering missions in militarily occupied territories such as the West Bank.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] They are often seen building or removing road blocks and building bases and fortifications.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Since 2005, they have also been used to demolish small houses.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The Israel Defense Forces added armor plating to the loader to protect it against rocks, stones, molotov cocktails, and light gunfire.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Rio de Janeiro's police elite squad Batalhão de Operações Policiais Especiais (BOPE) has acquired one wheel loader designed for military use to open routes and make way for the police in Rio de Janeiro's slums, which are controlled, and blocked, by drug dealers.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Several if not most countries have similar equipment.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The Dutch armed forces for instance use models like the Werklust WG18Edef, which weighs 15 tons, 2 more than the corresponding unarmored civilian model.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] In addition, the Dutch military previously used extra armor modules covering most of the window surface with steel for extra protection.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] These were however not popular with the crews due to low visibility.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The Turkish Army and Turkish Police used remote controlled armored wheel loader Tosun during the building of the Syria–Turkey barrier, the Operation Euphrates Shield, Operation Idlib Shield) and Operation Olive Branch.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] These loaders are a popular addition to tractors from 40 to 150 kW (50 to 200 hp).
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Its current 'drive-in' form was originally designed and developed in 1958 by a Swedish company named Ålö when they launched their Quicke loader.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Tractor loaders were developed to perform a multitude of farming tasks, and are popular due to their relatively low cost (compared to Telehandler) and high versatility.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Tractor loaders can be fitted with many attachments such as hydraulic grabs and spikes to assist with bale and silage handling, forks for pallet work, and buckets for more general farm activities.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Industrial tractor loaders equipped with box graders are marketed to contractors as **skip loaders**.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Abram Dietrich Thiessen of Eyebrow Saskatchewan in the 1940s built the first quick attach front-end loader.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Front-end loaders (FELs) are popular additions to compact utility tractors and farm tractors.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Compact utility tractors, also called CUTs, are small tractors, typically with 10 to 40 kW (18 to 50 hp) and used primarily for grounds maintenance and landscape chores.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] There are 2 primary designs of compact tractor FELs, the traditional dogleg designed style and the curved arm style.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] John Deere manufactures a semi-curved loader design that does not feature the one piece curved arm, but also is not of the traditional two piece design.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] New Holland introduced a compact loader with a one piece curved arm on its compact utility tractors, similar one piece curved arm loaders are now available on compact tractors on many brands including Case IH/Farmall, and some Montana and Kioti tractors.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Kubota markets traditional loader designs on most of its compact tractors but now features a semi-curved loader design similar to the John Deere loader design on several of its small tractors.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] While the front-end loaders on CUT size tractors are capable of many tasks, given their relatively small size and low capacities when compared to commercial loaders, the compact loaders can be made more useful with some simple options.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] A *toothbar* is commonly added to the front edge of a loader bucket to aid with digging.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Some loaders are equipped with a quick coupler, otherwise known as a *quick attach* *(QA)* system.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The *QA* system allows the bucket to be removed easily and other tools to be added in its place.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Common additions include a set of *pallet forks* for lifting pallets of goods or a *bale spear* for lifting hay bales.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] LHD (Load, Haul, Dump machine) is also a front-end loader but meant to be used for mine compact conditions, can handle various range of loads with varying size of buckets, and can be driven with electric motors as well as diesel engines.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] A skid loader is a small loader utilizing four wheels with hydraulic drive that directs power to either, or both, sides of the vehicle.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Very similar in appearance and design is the track loader, which utilizes a continuous track on either side of the vehicle instead of the wheels.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Since the expiration of Bobcat's patent on its quick-connect system, newer tractor models are standardizing that popular format for front-end attachments.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] A swingloader is a rigid frame loader with a swinging boom.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The Swingloader was invented in 1953 by German manufacturer Ahlmann with the AR1 model.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] The loader is able to lift on all sides and dump off on all sides.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Swingloaders are often used by the railroad industry to lay rail.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Like other loaders many attachments can be attached to the boom such as magnets, forks, and buckets.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] Smaller swingloaders can be used in farming applications for loading out.
[src:mining-automation/loader-equipment] A swinging boom is advantageous where space is limited as stability, mobility and space management are greatly increased over their articulated counterparts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining is also associated with a range of environmental, health, and social impacts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining activities contribute to land degradation, water contamination, and habitat loss.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In addition to environmental impacts, mining has been linked to occupational health risks and community displacement, and has affected low-income and marginalized populations.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Modern mining processes involve prospecting for ore bodies, analysis of the profit potential of a proposed mine, extraction of the desired materials, and final reclamation or restoration of the land after the mine is closed.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining materials are often obtained from ore bodies, lodes, veins, seams, reefs, or placer deposits.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The exploitation of these deposits for raw materials is dependent on investment, labor, energy, refining, and transportation costs.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining operations can have negative environmental impacts, both during mining and after the mine closes.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Hence, most of the world's nations have enacted regulations to reduce the impact; however, the outsized role of mining in generating business for often rural, remote, or economically depressed communities means that governments frequently fail to enforce them fully.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Work safety has long been a concern as well, and where enforced, modern practices have significantly improved safety in mines.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Unregulated, poorly regulated or illegal mining, especially in developing economies, frequently contributes to local human rights violations and environmental conflicts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining can also perpetuate political instability through resource conflicts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Since the beginning of civilization, people have used stone, clay, and, later, metals found near the Earth's surface.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] These were used to make early tools and weapons; for example, high-quality flint found in northern France, southern England, and Poland was used to create flint tools.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Flint mines have been found in chalk areas where seams of the stone were followed underground by shafts and galleries.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The mines at Grimes Graves and Krzemionki are especially famous, and like most other flint mines, are Neolithic in origin (c.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Other hard rocks mined or collected for axes included the greenstone of the Langdale axe industry based in the English Lake District.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The oldest-known mine in the archaeological record is the Ngwenya Mine in Eswatini (Swaziland), which radiocarbon dating indicates is about 41,000 - 43,000 years old.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] At this site Paleolithic humans mined hematite to make the red pigment ochre.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mines of a similar age in Hungary are believed to be sites where Neanderthals may have mined flint for weapons and tools.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Ancient Egyptians mined malachite at Maadi.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] At first, Egyptians used the bright green malachite stones for ornamentations and pottery.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Later, between 2613 and 2494 BC, large building projects required expeditions abroad to the Wadi Maghareh region to secure minerals and other resources not available in Egypt itself.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Quarries for turquoise and copper were also found at Wadi Hammamat, Tura, Aswan and various other Nubian sites, on the Sinai Peninsula, and at Timna.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Quarries for gypsum were found at the Umm el-Sawwan site; gypsum was used to make funerary items for private tombs.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Other minerals mined in Egypt from the Old Kingdom (2649–2134 BC) until the Roman Period (30 BC-AD 395) including granite, sandstone, limestone, basalt, travertine, gneiss, galena, and amethyst.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining in Egypt occurred in the earliest dynasties.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The gold mines of Nubia were among the most extensive of any in Ancient Egypt.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] These mines are described by the Greek author Diodorus Siculus, who mentions fire-setting as one method used to break down the hard rock holding the gold.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] One of the complexes is shown in one of the earliest known mining maps.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The miners crushed the ore and ground it to a fine powder before washing the powder for the gold dust known as the dry and wet attachment processes.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining in Europe has a very long history.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Examples include the silver mines of Laurium, which helped support the Greek city state of Athens.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Although they had over 20,000 slaves working them, their technology was essentially identical to their Bronze Age predecessors.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] At other mines, such as on the island of Thassos, marble was quarried by the Parians after they arrived in the 7th century BC.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The marble was shipped away and was later found by archaeologists to have been used in buildings including the tomb of Amphipolis.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Philip II of Macedon, the father of Alexander the Great, captured the gold mines of Mount Pangeo in 357 BC to fund his military campaigns.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] He also captured gold mines in Thrace for minting coinage, eventually producing 26 tons per year.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] However, it was the Romans who developed large-scale mining methods, especially the use of large volumes of water brought to the minehead by numerous aqueducts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The water was used for a variety of purposes, including removing overburden and rock debris (a process called hydraulic mining), washing comminuted (or crushed) ores, and driving simple machinery.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The Romans used hydraulic mining methods on a large scale to prospect for the veins of ore, especially using a now-obsolete form of mining known as hushing.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] They built numerous aqueducts to supply water to the minehead, where the water was stored in large reservoirs and tanks.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] When a full tank was opened, the flood of water sluiced away the overburden to expose the bedrock underneath and any gold-bearing veins.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The rock was then worked by fire-setting, heating it and then quenching it with a stream of water.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The resulting thermal shock cracked the rock, enabling it to be removed by further streams of water from the overhead tanks.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The Roman miners used similar methods to work cassiterite deposits in Cornwall and lead ore in the Pennines.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Sluicing methods were developed by the Romans in Spain in 25 AD to exploit large alluvial gold deposits, the largest site being at Las Medulas, where seven long aqueducts tapped local rivers and sluiced the deposits.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The Romans also exploited the silver present in the argentiferous galena in the mines of Cartagena (*Cartago Nova*), Linares (*Castulo*), Plasenzuela and Azuaga, among many others.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Spain was one of the most important mining regions, but all regions of the Roman Empire were exploited.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In Great Britain the natives had mined minerals for millennia, but after the Roman conquest, the scale of the operations increased dramatically, as the Romans needed Britannia's resources, especially gold, silver, tin, and lead.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Roman techniques were not limited to surface mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] They followed the ore veins underground once opencast mining was no longer feasible.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] At Dolaucothi they stoped out the veins and drove adits through bare rock to drain the stopes.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The same adits were also used to ventilate the workings, especially important when fire-setting was used.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] At other parts of the site, they penetrated the water table and dewatered the mines using several kinds of machines, especially reverse overshot water-wheels.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] These were used extensively in the copper mines at Rio Tinto in Spain, where one sequence comprised 16 such wheels arranged in pairs, and lifting water about 24 metres (79 ft).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] They worked as treadmills with miners standing on the top slats.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Many examples of such devices have been found in old Roman mines, and some examples are now preserved in the British Museum and the National Museum of Wales.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining as an industry underwent dramatic changes in medieval Europe.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The mining industry in the early Middle Ages was primarily focused on extracting copper and iron.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Other precious metals were also used, mainly for gilding or coinage.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Initially, many metals were obtained through open-pit mining, and ore was primarily extracted from shallow depths, rather than through deep mine shafts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Around the 14th century, the growing use of weapons, armour, stirrups, and horseshoes greatly increased the demand for iron.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Medieval knights, for example, were often laden with up to 100 pounds (45 kg) of plate or chain link armour in addition to swords, lances and other weapons.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The overwhelming dependency on iron for military purposes spurred iron production and extraction processes.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The silver crisis of 1465 occurred when all mines had reached depths at which the shafts could no longer be pumped dry with the available technology.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Although an increased use of banknotes, credit and copper coins during this period did decrease the value of, and dependence on, precious metals, gold and silver remained vital to the story of medieval mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Due to differences in social structure, the increasing extraction of mineral deposits spread from central Europe to England in the mid-sixteenth century.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] On the continent, mineral deposits belonged to the crown, and this regalian right was stoutly maintained.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] But in England, royal mining rights were restricted to gold and silver (of which England had virtually no deposits) by a judicial decision of 1568 and a law in 1688.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] England had iron, zinc, copper, lead, and tin ores.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Landlords who owned the base metals and coal under their estates had a strong incentive to extract these metals or lease the deposits and collect royalties from mine operators.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] English, German, and Dutch capital combined to finance extraction and refining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Hundreds of German technicians and skilled workers were brought over; in 1642, a colony of 4,000 foreigners was mining and smelting copper at Keswick in the northwestern mountains.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Use of water power in the form of water mills was extensive.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The water mills were employed to crush ore, raise ore from shafts, and ventilate galleries by powering giant bellows.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Black powder was first used in mining in Selmecbánya, Kingdom of Hungary (now Banská Štiavnica, Slovakia) in 1627.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Black powder allowed blasting of rock and earth to loosen and reveal ore veins.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Blasting was much faster than fire-setting and allowed the mining of previously impenetrable metals and ores.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In 1762, one of the world's first mining academies was established in the same town.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The widespread adoption of agricultural innovations such as the iron plowshare, as well as the growing use of metal as a building material, was also a driving force in the tremendous growth of the iron industry during this period.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The Spanish often used inventions such as the arrastra to pulverize ore after mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] This device was powered by animals and employed the same principles as grain threshing.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Much of the knowledge of medieval mining techniques comes from books such as Biringuccio's *De la pirotechnia* and, probably most importantly, from Georg Agricola's *De re metallica* (1556).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] These books detail many different mining methods used in German and Saxon mines.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] A prime issue in medieval mines, which Agricola explains in detail, was the removal of water from mining shafts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] As miners dug deeper to access new veins, flooding became a very real obstacle.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The mining industry became dramatically more efficient and prosperous with the invention of mechanically- and animal-driven pumps.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Iron metallurgy in Africa dates back over four thousand years.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Gold became an important commodity for Africa during the trans-Saharan gold trade from the 7th century to the 14th century.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Gold was often traded to Mediterranean economies that demanded gold and could supply salt, even though much of Africa was abundant with salt due to the mines and resources in the Sahara.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The trade of gold for salt was primarily used to promote trade between different economies.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Since the Great Trek in the 19th century, after, gold and diamond mining in Southern Africa has had major political and economic impacts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The Democratic Republic of Congo is the largest producer of diamonds in Africa, with an estimated 12 million carats in 2019.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Other types of mining reserves in Africa include cobalt, bauxite, iron ore, coal, and copper.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Gold and coal mining started in Australia and New Zealand in the 19th century.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Nickel has become important in the economy of New Caledonia.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In Fiji, in 1934, the Emperor Gold Mining Company Ltd. established operations at Vatukoula, followed in 1935 by the Loloma Gold Mines, N.L., and then by Fiji Mines Development Ltd.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] These developments ushered in a "mining boom", with gold production rising more than a hundred-fold, from 931.4 oz in 1934 to 107,788.5 oz in 1939, an order of magnitude then comparable to the combined output of New Zealand and Australia's eastern states.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] During prehistoric times, early Americans mined large quantities of copper along Lake Superior's Keweenaw Peninsula and on nearby Isle Royale; metallic copper remained near the surface into colonial times.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Indigenous peoples used Lake Superior copper from at least 5,000 years ago; copper tools, arrowheads, and other artifacts that were part of an extensive native trade-network have been discovered.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In addition, obsidian, flint, and other minerals were mined, worked, and traded.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Early French explorers who encountered the sites made no use of the metals due to the difficulties of transporting them, but the copper was eventually traded throughout the continent along major river routes.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In the early colonial history of the Americas, "native gold and silver was quickly expropriated and sent back to Spain in fleets of gold- and silver-laden galleons", the gold and silver originating mostly from mines in Central and South America.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Turquoise dated at 700 AD was mined in pre-Columbian America; in the Cerillos Mining District in New Mexico, an estimate of "about 15,000 tons of rock had been removed from Mt.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In 1727 Louis Denys (Denis) (1675–1741), sieur de La Ronde – brother of Simon-Pierre Denys de Bonaventure and the son-in-law of René Chartier – took command of Fort La Pointe at Chequamegon Bay; where natives informed him of an island of copper.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] La Ronde obtained permission from the French crown to operate mines in 1733, becoming "the first practical miner on Lake Superior"; seven years later, mining was halted by an outbreak between Sioux and Chippewa tribes.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining in the United States became widespread in the 19th century, and the United States Congress passed the General Mining Act of 1872 to encourage mining of federal lands.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] As with the California Gold Rush in the mid-19th century, mining for minerals and precious metals, along with ranching, became a driving factor in the U.S.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Westward Expansion to the Pacific coast.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] With the exploration of the West, mining camps sprang up and "expressed a distinctive spirit, an enduring legacy to the new nation"; Gold Rushers would experience the same problems as the Land Rushers of the transient West that preceded them.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Aided by railroads, many people traveled West for work opportunities in mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Western cities such as Denver and Sacramento originated as mining towns.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] When new areas were explored, it was usually the gold (placer and then lode) and then silver that were taken into possession and extracted first.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Other metals would often wait for railroads or canals, as coarse gold dust and nuggets do not require smelting and are easy to identify and transport.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In the early 20th century, the gold and silver rush to the western United States also stimulated mining for coal as well as base metals such as copper, lead, and iron.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Areas in modern Montana, Utah, Arizona, and later Alaska became major suppliers of copper to the world, which was increasingly in demand for electrical and household goods.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Canada's mining industry grew more slowly than did the United States due to limitations in transportation, capital, and U.S. competition; Ontario was the major producer of the early 20th century with nickel, copper, and gold.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] After declines in production, another boom in mining occurred in the 1960s.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In the early 21st century, Australia remains a major world mineral producer.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] As the 21st century begins, a globalized mining industry dominated by large multinational corporations has emerged.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Peak minerals and environmental impacts have also become a concern.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Different elements, particularly rare-earth minerals, have begun to increase in demand as a result of new technologies.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In 2023, 8.5 billion metric tons of coal were extracted from the Earth's crust.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] However, as the global economy transitions away from fossil fuels and toward a more sustainable future, the demand for metals is set to skyrocket.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Between 2022 and 2050, an estimated 7 billion metric tons of metals will need to be extracted.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Steel will account for the largest portion of this total at 5 billion tons, followed by aluminum at 950 million tons, copper at 650 million tons, graphite at 170 million tons, nickel at 100 million tons, and other metals.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Notably, the energy expenditure required to extract these metals will soon surpass that of coal mining, highlighting the growing importance of sustainable metal extraction practices.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The process of mining, from the discovery of an ore body through mineral extraction to the final return of the land to its natural state, consists of several distinct steps.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The first is the discovery of the ore body, carried out through prospecting or exploration to identify and define its extent, location, and value.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] This leads to a mathematical resource estimation of the deposit's size and grade.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] This estimation is used to conduct a pre-feasibility study to determine the theoretical economics of the ore deposit.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] This identifies early on whether further investment in estimation and engineering studies is warranted and highlights key risks and areas for further work.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The next step is to conduct a feasibility study to evaluate the project's financial viability, technical and financial risks, and robustness.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Commodity price volatility tends to reduce the feasibility of mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] This is when the mining company decides whether to develop the mine or walk away from the project.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The proportion of a deposit that is economically recoverable is dependent on the enrichment factor of the ore in the area.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] To gain access to the mineral deposit within an area, it is often necessary to mine through or remove waste material, which is not of immediate interest to the miner.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The total movement of ore and waste constitutes the mining process.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Often, more waste than ore is mined during the life of a mine, depending on the nature and location of the ore body.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Waste removal and placement are major costs to the mining operator, so a detailed characterization of the waste material forms an essential part of the geological exploration program for a mining operation.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Once the analysis determines that a given ore body is worth recovering, development begins to provide access to it.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The mine buildings and processing plants are built, and any necessary equipment is obtained.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The operation of the mine to recover the ore begins and continues as long as the company operating the mine finds it economical to do so.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Once all the ore that the mine can produce profitably is recovered, reclamation can begin, to make the land used by the mine suitable for future use.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Technical and economic challenges notwithstanding, successful mine development must also address human factors.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Working conditions are important to success, especially with respect to exposure to dust, radiation, noise, explosive hazards, and vibration, as well as illumination standards.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining must increasingly address environmental and community impacts, including psychological and sociological dimensions.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] White (1909–1971) broadened the focus to the "total environment of mining", including reference to community development around mining, and how mining is portrayed to an urban society, which depends on the industry, although seemingly unaware of this dependency.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] He stated, "[I]n the past, mining engineers have not been called upon to study the psychological, sociological, and personal problems of their own industry – aspects that nowadays are assuming tremendous importance.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining techniques can be divided into two common excavation types: surface mining and sub-surface (underground) mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Modern surface mining (also called open pit) is much more common and produces, for example, 85% of minerals (excluding petroleum and natural gas) in the United States, including 98% of metallic ores.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Both types of ore deposit, placer or lode, are mined by both surface and underground methods.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Some mining, including much of the rare earth element and uranium mining, is done by less common methods, such as in-situ leaching.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] This technique involves neither digging at the surface nor underground.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The extraction of target minerals by this technique requires that they be soluble, e.g., potash, potassium chloride, sodium chloride, sodium sulfate, which dissolve in water.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Some minerals, such as copper minerals and uranium oxide, require acid or carbonate solutions to dissolve.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Explosives have been used in surface mining and sub-surface mining to blast out rock and ore intended for processing.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The most common explosive used in mining is ammonium nitrate.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Between 1870 and 1920, in Queensland, Australia, an increase in mining accidents led to more safety measures surrounding the use of explosives for mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In the United States of America, between 1990 and 1999, about 22.3 billion kilograms of explosives were used in mining quarrying and other industries; Moreover "coal mining used 66.4%, nonmetal mining and quarrying 13.5%, metal mining 10.4%, construction 7.1%, and all other users 2.6%".
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] ASM involves miners who may or may not be officially employed.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Although there can be large numbers of miners working at a mining site, they typically work in small teams according to a customary system of organisation that includes a manager, skilled and unskilled labour.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] While the terms are generally used interchangeably or synonymously, by definition 'artisanal mining' refers to purely manual labor while 'small-scale mining' typically involves larger operations and some use of mechanical or industrial tools.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] While there is no completely coherent definition for ASM, artisanal mining generally includes miners who are not officially employed by a mining company and use their own resources to mine.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] As such, they are part of an informal economy.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] ASM also includes, in small-scale mining, enterprises or individuals that employ workers for mining, but who generally still use similar manually-intensive methods as artisanal miners (such as working with hand tools).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In addition, ASM can be characterized as distinct from large-scale mining (LSM) by less efficient extraction of pure minerals from the ore, lower wages, decreased occupational safety, benefits, and health standards for miners, and a lack of environmental protection measures.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] ASM has on occasion been evaluated positively in terms of negligible capital outflow, the employment it generates and the connection it has with local society and economy in contrast with the enclave economies of some LSM.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Artisanal miners often undertake the activity of mining seasonally.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] For example, crops are planted in the rainy season, and mining is pursued in the dry season.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] However, they also frequently travel to mining areas and work year-round.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Shock-push (poverty-driven, following conflict or natural disasters).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] ASM is an important socio-economic sector for the rural poor in many developing nations, many of whom have few other options for supporting their families.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Over 90% of the world's mining workforce are engaged in ASM, with an estimated 40.5 million people directly engaged in ASM, from over 80 countries in the global south.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] More than 150 million people indirectly depend on ASM for their livelihood.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] 70–80% of small-scale miners are informal, and approximately 30% are women, although this ranges in certain countries and commodities from 5% to 80%.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Surface mining is done by removing surface vegetation, dirt, and bedrock to reach buried ore deposits.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Most placer deposits, because they are shallowly buried, are mined by surface methods.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Finally, landfill mining involves excavating and processing landfill sites.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Landfill mining has been thought of as a long-term solution to methane emissions and local pollution.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] High-wall mining, which evolved from auger mining, is another form of surface mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In high wall mining, the remaining part of a coal seam previously exploited by other surface-mining techniques has too much overburden to be removed but can still be profitably exploited from the side of the artificial cliff made by previous mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] A typical cycle alternates sumping, which undercuts the seam, and shearing, which raises and lowers the cutter-head boom to cut the entire height of the coal seam.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] As the coal recovery cycle continues, the cutter head is progressively advanced further into the coal seam.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] High wall mining can produce thousands of tons of coal in contour-strip operations with narrow benches, previously mined areas, trench mine applications, and steep-dip seams.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Subsurface mining involves digging tunnels or shafts into the earth to access buried ore deposits.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Ore for processing and waste rock for disposal are brought to the surface through the tunnels and shafts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Subsurface mining can be classified by the type of access shafts used, the extraction method, or the technique for reaching the mineral deposit.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Drift mining uses horizontal access tunnels, slope mining uses diagonally sloping access shafts, and shaft mining uses vertical access shafts.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining in hard and soft rock formations requires different techniques.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Other methods include shrinkage stope mining, which is mining upward, creating a sloping underground room, long wall mining, which is grinding a long ore surface underground, and room and pillar mining, which is removing ore from rooms while leaving pillars in place to support the roof of the room.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Room-and-pillar mining often leads to retreat mining, in which supporting pillars are removed as miners retreat, allowing the room to cave in and thereby loosening more ore.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Additional sub-surface mining methods include hard rock mining, borehole mining, drift and fill mining, long hole slope mining, sub-level caving, and block caving.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Heavy machinery is used in mining to explore and develop sites, to remove and stockpile overburden, to break and remove rocks of various hardness and toughness, to process the ore, and to carry out reclamation projects after the mine is closed.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Bulldozers, drills, explosives, and trucks are all necessary for excavating the land.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In the case of placer mining, unconsolidated gravel, or alluvium, is fed into machinery consisting of a hopper and a shaking screen or trommel, which frees the desired minerals from the waste gravel.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The minerals are then concentrated using sluices or jigs.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Large drills are used to sink shafts, excavate stopes, and obtain samples for analysis, and to extract natural gas (see Fracking).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Trams are used to transport miners, minerals, and waste.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Lifts carry miners into and out of mines, move rock and ore out, and move machinery in and out of underground mines.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Huge trucks, shovels, and cranes are employed in surface mining to move large quantities of overburden and ore.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Processing plants use large crushers, mills, reactors, roasters, and other equipment to consolidate the mineral-rich material and extract the desired compounds and metals from the ore.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Once the mineral is extracted, it is often then processed.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The science of extractive metallurgy is a specialized branch of metallurgy that studies the extraction of valuable metals from ores, particularly by chemical or mechanical means.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mineral processing (or mineral dressing) is a specialized area in the science of metallurgy that studies the mechanical means of crushing, grinding, and washing that enable the separation (extractive metallurgy) of valuable metals or minerals from their gangue (waste material).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Processing of placer ore material consists of gravity-based separation methods, such as Sluice boxes.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Only minor shaking or washing may be necessary to disaggregate (unclump) the sands or gravels before processing.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Processing ore from a lode mine, whether surface or subsurface, requires crushing and pulverizing the ore before extraction of the valuable minerals begins.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] After the ore is crushed, the valuable minerals are recovered using one or a combination of mechanical and chemical techniques.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Since most metals are present in ores as oxides or sulfides, the metal needs to be reduced to its metallic form.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] This can be accomplished through chemical means such as smelting or through electrolytic reduction, as in the case of aluminium.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Geometallurgy combines the geologic sciences with extractive metallurgy and mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In 2018, led by Chemistry and Biochemistry professor Bradley D.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Smith, University of Notre Dame researchers "invented a new class of molecules whose shape and size enable them to capture and contain precious metal ions," reported in a study published by the Journal of the American Chemical Society.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The new method "converts gold-containing ore into chloroauric acid and extracts it using an industrial solvent.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] London is the headquarters of Anglo American.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Melbourne is the headquarters of the world's two largest mining companies BHP and Rio Tinto.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The US mining industry is also large and dominated by extraction of coal and other nonmetal minerals (e.g., rock and sand), and various regulations have worked to reduce the significance of mining in the United States.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In 2007, the total market capitalization of mining companies was reported at US$962 billion, which compares to a total global market cap of publicly traded companies of about US$50 trillion in 2007.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In 2002, Chile and Peru were reportedly the major mining countries of South America.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The mineral industry of Africa includes the mining of various minerals; it produces relatively little of the industrial metals copper, lead, and zinc, but according to one estimate has as a percent of world reserves 40% of gold, 60% of cobalt, and 90% of the world's platinum group metals.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining in India is a significant part of that country's economy.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In the developed world, mining in Australia, with BHP founded and headquartered in the country, and mining in Canada, are particularly significant.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] For rare earth minerals mining, China reportedly controlled 95% of production in 2013.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] While individual entrepreneurs or small businesses can conduct exploration and mining, most modern-day mines are large enterprises that require substantial capital to establish.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Consequently, the mining sector of the industry is dominated by large, often multinational companies, most of which are publicly listed.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] It can be argued that what is referred to as the 'mining industry' comprises two sectors: one specializing in the exploration of new resources and the other in mining those resources.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The exploration sector is typically made up of individuals and small mineral resource companies, called "juniors", that depend on venture capital.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The mining sector comprises large multinational companies that are sustained by production from their operations.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Various other industries, such as equipment manufacturing, environmental testing, and metallurgical analysis, rely on and support the mining industry worldwide.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Canadian stock exchanges have a particular focus on mining companies, particularly junior exploration companies, through Toronto's TSX Venture Exchange; Canadian companies raise capital on these exchanges and then invest the money in exploration globally.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Some have argued that below juniors, there exists a substantial sector of illegitimate companies primarily focused on manipulating stock prices.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining operations can be grouped into five major categories based on the resources they exploit.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] These are oil and gas extraction, coal mining, metal ore mining, nonmetallic mineral mining and quarrying, and mining support activities.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Of all of these categories, oil and gas extraction remains one of the largest in terms of its global economic importance.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Prospecting potential mining sites, a vital area of concern for the mining industry, is now done using sophisticated new technologies such as seismic prospecting and remote-sensing satellites.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining is heavily affected by the prices of the commodity minerals, which are often volatile.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The 2000s commodities boom ("commodities supercycle") increased commodity prices, driving aggressive mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In addition, the price of gold increased dramatically in the 2000s, which increased gold mining; for example, one study found that conversion of forest in the Amazon increased six-fold from the period 2003–2006 (292 ha/yr) to the period 2006–2009 (1,915 ha/yr), largely due to artisanal mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Regarding their valuation and stock market characteristics, see Valuation (finance) § Valuation of mining projects.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The World Bank has been involved in mining since 1955, mainly through grants from its International Bank for Reconstruction and Development, with the Bank's Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency offering political risk insurance.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Between 1955 and 1990 it provided about $2 billion to fifty mining projects, broadly categorized as reform and rehabilitation, greenfield mine construction, mineral processing, technical assistance, and engineering.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] These projects have been criticized, particularly the Ferro Carajas project of Brazil, begun in 1981.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The World Bank established mining codes intended to increase foreign investment; in 1988, it solicited feedback from 45 mining companies on how to increase their involvement.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In 1992, the World Bank began to push for privatization of government-owned mining companies with a new set of codes, beginning with its report *The Strategy for African Mining*.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In 1997, Latin America's largest miner Companhia Vale do Rio Doce (CVRD) was privatized.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The codes based on this report are influential in the legislation of developing nations.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The new codes are intended to encourage development through tax holidays, zero customs duties, reduced income taxes, and related measures.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The results of these codes were analyzed by a group from the University of Quebec, which concluded that the codes promote foreign investment but "fall very short of permitting sustainable development".
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The observed negative correlation between natural resources and economic development is known as the resource curse.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Safety has long been a concern in the mining business, especially in sub-surface mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The Courrières mine disaster, Europe's worst mining accident, involved the death of 1,099 miners in Northern France on March 10, 1906.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] This disaster was surpassed only by the Benxihu Colliery accident in China on April 26, 1942, which killed 1,549 miners.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Although mining has become substantially safer than it was in previous decades, mining accidents still occur.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Government figures indicate that around 5,000 Chinese miners die in accidents each year, while other reports have suggested a figure as high as 20,000.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Between 1870 and 1920 in Queensland, Australia, an increase in mining accidents led to more safety measures regarding the use of explosives in mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), safety concerns have been raised for both those who work in the mines and those who live in the surrounding areas.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Workers are usually seen with a mustard-colored powder that turned out to be "...dried sulfuric acid, [which] they use in the mine to process the [mineral] ores.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] In South Africa, issues are similar to those in the DRC.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Miners are exposed to silica dust, which "increases the risk of pulmonary tuberculosis," with a tuberculosis rate of "over 1,000 per 100,000." "Mine shafts themselves are crowded and poorly-ventilated, but so are hostels where over a dozen men can share a small room.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] These conditions are highly conducive to infection; the rate of recurrent tuberculosis in a recent South African prospective cohort of 600 miners was about 8 per 100 person-years," which increases the risk of tuberculosis spreading in both mining and living locations.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining accidents continue worldwide, including incidents that have caused dozens of fatalities at a time, such as the 2007 Ulyanovskaya Mine disaster in Russia, the 2009 Heilongjiang mine explosion in China, and the 2010 Upper Big Branch Mine disaster in the United States.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda (NORA) to identify and provide intervention strategies regarding occupational health and safety issues.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] There are numerous occupational hazards associated with mining, including exposure to rockdust, which can lead to diseases such as silicosis, asbestosis, and pneumoconiosis.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Gases in the mine can lead to asphyxiation and have a risk of ignition.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Mining equipment can generate considerable noise, putting workers at risk for hearing loss.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Cave-ins, rock falls, and exposure to excess heat are also known hazards.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The NIOSH Recommended Exposure Limit (REL) of noise is 85 dBA with a 3 dBA exchange rate, and the MSHA Permissible Exposure Limit (PEL) is 90 dBA with a 5 dBA exchange rate as an 8-hour time-weighted average.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] NIOSH has found that 25% of noise-exposed workers in Mining, Quarrying, and Oil and Gas Extraction have hearing impairment.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] The prevalence of hearing loss increased by 1% from 1991 to 2001 within these workers.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Noise studies have been conducted in several mining environments.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Stageloaders (84-102 dBA), shearers (85-99 dBA), auxiliary fans (84–120 dBA), continuous mining machines (78–109 dBA), and roof bolters (92–103 dBA) represent some of the noisiest equipment in underground coal mines.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Dragline oilers, dozer operators, and welders using air arcing were occupations with the highest noise exposures among surface coal miners.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p01] Coal mines had the highest hearing loss injury likelihood.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Environmental impact of mining can occur at local, regional, and global scales through direct and indirect mining practices.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining can cause erosion, sinkholes, loss of biodiversity, or the contamination of soil, groundwater, and surface water by chemicals emitted from mining processes.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These processes also affect the atmosphere through carbon emissions which contributes to climate change.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining can provide various advantages to societies, yet it can also spark conflicts, particularly regarding land use both above and below the surface.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining operations remain rigorous and intrusive, often resulting in significant environmental impacts on local ecosystems and broader implications for planetary environmental health.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] To accommodate mines and associated infrastructure, land is cleared extensively, consuming significant energy and water resources, emitting air pollutants, and producing hazardous waste.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] According to The World Counts page "The amount of resources mined from Earth is up from 39.3 billion tons in 2002.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] A 55 percent increase in less than 20 years.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] This puts Earth's natural resources under heavy pressure.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining activities can significantly contribute to water pollution through the release of heavy metals and toxic substances into surrounding waterways.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Processes such as acid mine drainage occur when sulfide minerals are exposed to air and water, producing acidic runoff that carry contaminants such as arsenic, lead, and mercury into rivers and groundwater.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] This pollution can harm aquatic ecosystems, reduce water quality, and pose risks to human health, particularly in communities that rely on local water sources for drinking and agriculture.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In some cases, contamination persists long after mining operations have stopped, making remediation difficult and costly.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Water pollution from mining can also result from the storage and disposal of mine waste, including tailings and waste rock, which may contain hazardous chemicals and heavy metals.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Failures or leaks in tailings storage facilities have released large volumes of contaminated materials into rivers and surrounding ecosystems, causing widespread environmental damage.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Even without major failures, runoff from mining sites can transport pollutants into nearby waterways during rainfall events, further degrading water quality.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Abandoned mine sites are a particularly significant source of ongoing contamination, as untreated drainage can continue to release acidic and metal laden water into the environment for decades after closure.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] This is important because water is vital for many communities' survival.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Fresh rivers are a source of fish and fresh water.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] However, the water isn't fresh anymore, it is heavily polluted by toxic runoff from nearby mines.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Researcher Siddharth Kara explains that in the context of cobalt mining in the Democratic Republic of Congo, "water is heavily polluted, a condition that local residents attribute to toxic runoff from nearby mines.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The environmental researcher at the University of Lubumbashi whom I met after my visit to Kipushi, Germain, took samples from the river water near Mupanja and found particularly high levels of lead, chromium, cobalt, and industrial acids.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] When I inspected the water, it had an unnaturally dark color and was topped with slicks and sludge".
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Ore mills generate large amounts of waste, called tailings.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] For example, 99 tons of waste is generated per ton of copper, with even higher ratios in gold mining – because only 5.3 g of gold is extracted per ton of ore, a ton of gold produces 200,000 tons of tailings.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] (As time goes on and richer deposits are exhausted – and technology improves – this number is going down to .5 g and less.) These tailings can be toxic.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Tailings, which are usually produced as a slurry, are most commonly dumped into ponds made from naturally existing valleys.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These ponds are secured by impoundments (dams or embankment dams).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In 2000, it was estimated that 3,500 tailings impoundments existed, and that every year, 2 to 5 major failures and 35 minor failures occurred.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] For example, in the Marcopper mining disaster at least 2 million tons of tailings were released into a local river.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In 2015, Barrick Gold Corporation spilled over 1 million liters of cyanide into a total of five rivers in Argentina near their Veladero mine.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Since 2007 in central Finland, the Talvivaara Terrafame polymetal mine's waste effluent and leaks of saline mine water have resulted in ecological collapse of a nearby lake.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Subaqueous tailings disposal is another option.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The mining industry has argued that submarine tailings disposal (STD), which disposes of tailings in the sea, is ideal because it avoids the risks of tailings ponds.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The practice is illegal in the United States and Canada, but it is used in the developing world.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The waste is classified as either sterile or mineralized, with acid-generating potential, and the movement and storage of this material form a major part of the mine planning process.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] When an economic cut-off determines the mineralised package, the near-grade mineralised waste is usually dumped separately, with a view to later treatment should market conditions change, and it becomes economically viable.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Civil engineering design parameters are used for waste dump design, with special conditions applying to high-rainfall and seismically active areas.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Waste dump designs must meet all regulatory requirements of the country in whose jurisdiction the mine is located.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] It is also common practice to rehabilitate dumps to an internationally acceptable standard, which, in some cases, means applying higher standards than the local regulatory standard.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Abandoned and inactive mines can continue to create environmental risks after operations have ended.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] They can have detrimental effects on soil, water, plants, and animals.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Acid mine drainage, which occurs when minerals are exposed to air and water, can result in the long-term release of acid water and heavy metals into nearby water.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These effects can continue for decades or longer, contaminating drinking water and harming ecosystems.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The National Park Service explains that, "Soils and water contaminated with heavy metals or chemicals from mineral processing may be harmful to wildlife.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These contaminants can become increasingly concentrated in animals higher up the food chain in a process called biomagnification.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Affected animals could die or become unable to reproduce".
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Countries with strongly enforced mining regulations commonly require environmental impact assessment, development of environmental management plans, and mine closure planning before beginning mine operations.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Environmental monitoring during operation and after closure may also be required.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Government regulations may not be well enforced, especially in the developing world.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Differences between countries in mining regulation stringency incentivize mining in polution havens, worsening the global impact of mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] For major mining companies and any company seeking international financing, there are some other mechanisms to enforce environmental standards.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These generally relate to financing standards such as the Equator Principles, IFC environmental standards, and criteria for Socially responsible investing.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining companies have used this oversight from the financial sector to argue for some level of industry self-regulation.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The mining industry has provided funding to various conservation groups, some of which have been working with conservation agendas that are at odds with an emerging acceptance of the rights of indigenous people – particularly the right to make land-use decisions.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Certification of mines with good practices is issued by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] For example, ISO 9000 and ISO 14001, which certify an "auditable environmental management system", involve brief inspections, although they have been criticized for lacking rigor.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Certification is also available through Ceres' Global Reporting Initiative, but these reports are voluntary and unverified.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Miscellaneous other certification programs exist for various projects, typically through nonprofit groups.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The purpose of a 2012 EPS PEAKS paper was to provide evidence on policies managing ecological costs and maximize socio-economic benefits of mining using host country regulatory initiatives.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] New regulations and a process of legislative reforms aim to improve the harmonization and stability of the mining sector in mineral-rich countries.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] New legislation for mining industry in African countries still appears to be an issue, but has the potential to be solved, when a consensus is reached on the best approach.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] By the beginning of the 21st century, the booming and increasingly complex mining sector in mineral-rich countries was providing only slight benefits to local communities, especially given the sustainability issues.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Increasing debate and influence by NGOs and local communities called for new approaches which would also include disadvantaged communities, and work towards sustainable development even after mine closure (including transparency and revenue management).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] By the early 2000s, community development issues and resettlement had become mainstream concerns in World Bank mining projects.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining-industry expansion after mineral prices increased in 2003, and also potential fiscal revenues in those countries created an omission in the other economic sectors in terms of finances and development.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Furthermore, this highlighted the regional and local demand for mining revenues and the inability of sub-national governments to use them effectively.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The Fraser Institute (a Canadian think tank) has highlighted the environmental protection laws in developing countries, as well as voluntary efforts by mining companies to improve their environmental impact.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In 2007, the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative (EITI) was mainstreamed in all countries cooperating with the World Bank in mining industry reform.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The EITI operates and was implemented with the support of the EITI multi-donor trust fund, managed by the World Bank.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The EITI aims to increase transparency in transactions between governments and companies in extractive industries by monitoring the revenues and benefits between industries and recipient governments.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Therefore, the outcome assessment in terms of failure or success of the new EITI regulation does not only "rest on the government's shoulders" but also on civil society and companies.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] However, implementation has issues; inclusion or exclusion of artisanal mining and small-scale mining (ASM) from the EITI, and how to deal with "non-cash" payments made by companies to subnational governments.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Furthermore, the disproportionate revenues the mining industry can bring to the comparatively small number of people that it employs, causes other problems, like a lack of investment in other less lucrative sectors, leading to swings in government revenue because of volatility in the oil markets.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Artisanal mining is clearly an issue in EITI Countries such as the Central African Republic, D.R.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Congo, Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone – i.e., almost half of the mining countries implementing the EITI.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Increased public awareness, with the government acting as a bridge between the public and the initiative to ensure a successful policy outcome, is an important element to consider.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] There is a lack of law enforcement in various countries.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] For example, "although South Africa has strong regulations to avoid potential mining impacts, lack of enforcement and corruption have been barriers to combating social and environmental injustices," leading to unsafe working conditions for many miners (see Safety Section).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In the DRC, "more than half of the DRC's natural resource exports are not officially recorded because of tax evasion and state institutions' lack of governance capacity," and "90% of minerals come from artisanal miners," which are indigenous people.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining operations often intersect with land rights in complex and sometimes contentious ways.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In many countries, land ownership and mineral resource ownership are legally separated, with mineral rights usually vested in the state, while individuals or communities may own land.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] This creates a situation in which communities may have legal ownership of the surface land but limited control over mineral extraction beneath it.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Customary land tenure, prevalent in many rural areas, often governs land use and inheritance.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining in these areas can disrupt farming, grazing, and culturally significant sites, and communities without formal titles may be vulnerable to displacement or inadequate compensation.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In addition to the environmental impacts of mining processes, a prominent criticism of this form of extractive practice and of mining companies concerns the human rights abuses occurring at mining sites and in communities near them.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In addition, many of these legal structures disproportionally harm indigenous communities.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These are all examples of environmental justice.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Environmental justice refers to the fair distribution of environmental benefits and burdens, as well as the involvement of all communities in environmental decision making.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In the context of mining, environmental justice concerns arise when environmental and health impacts disproportionately affect low income, indigenous, or marginalized populations.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These impacts include exposure to toxic substances, displacement from land, and limited access to political or legal resources to address this environmental harm.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining operations are often located in regions where communities have less political power, raising concerns about inequality and long-term environmental and social consequences.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Mining related environmental impacts are often unevenly distributed, disproportionately affecting rural and low income communities.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Abandoned mines, toxic waste, and water contamination can persist long after mining operations stop, creating long-term burdens on communities.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The world is already at risk for water deprivation, so almost every population and community is at risk.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Communities affected by mining require fair rights and resources to help prevent environmental contamination from affecting them but also everyone (Blais, 2024).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In the Democratic Republic of the Congo, mining, specifically for cobalt, has been associated with significant human rights concerns.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Artisanal and small-scale mining operations often involve hazardous working conditions, including exposure to toxic dust, risk of tunnel collapses, and a lack of protective equipment.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Reports have documented the use of child labor and low wages in mining areas.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Workers and nearby communities also face long-term health risks due to environmental contamination from mining activities.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These conditions have raised concerns from nearby communities regarding supply chains and the responsibility of multinational corporations involved in mineral sourcing.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Conditions in the mines and nearby communities have become difficult places to live, work, and stay in.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] While digging in the mines, it is difficult to predict when walls of the mines will collapse and cause irreversible injuries.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Researcher Siddharth Kara provides examples of such issues in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, explaining that "While [miners] were digging, one of the walls of the pit collapsed. [Miners] were buried in an avalanche of stones and dirt".
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] After this collapse, "The clinic did not have any painkillers other than acetaminophen, which was incapable of dulling his discomfort.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The clinic also did not have antibiotics to treat a potential infection, nor an x-ray machine with which to determine the extent of the bone damage" (Kara, 2023).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Because of the damage from the mine and the lack of accessible healthcare, people suffer from irreversible damage for the rest of their lives, making them unable to walk, therefore unable to work in the mines again and make money to support their family.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Working in the mines puts you at risk for injury and even death.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] From the Human Rights Research Center, Erina Bazán López, a motivated scholar, writes about the recent toll of cobalt mining on people in the Congo.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] "On November 15, a makeshift bridge on a cobalt and copper mine collapsed in Lualaba province in Democratic Republic of Congo, killing at least 32 people.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The disasters occurred in a semi-industrial mine in the southeastern Kalando area of the province, where a comprehensive restriction prohibiting access had been previously put in place due to heavy rains that exacerbated risks of landslides in the territory (Bazán López, 2025).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] There are many of these incidents happening in the DRC throughout the years, often unpredictable.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Artisanal miners, who account for a substantial portion of cobalt production in the country, often work in informal settings with limited regulatory oversight, making enforcement of labor and safety standards difficult.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In some mining regions, individuals rely on daily extraction for income, creating economic pressures that contribute to unsafe practices and the involvement of children in mining activities.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Environmental contamination from mining operations, including the release of heavy metals into soil and water, has been linked to broader public health concerns in surrounding communities.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These conditions have prompted increased international attention and calls for greater supply chain transparency, corporate due diligence, and stronger regulatory frameworks to help improve labor conditions and reduce environmental health risks.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] There has been an increase in child labor in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Children start working in the mines when they are very young, experiencing the true conditions of the mines including toxic air, injuries, and an overall unsafe environment for children to work in.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The main reason for child labor is due to the need for income.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Because people working in the mines only get paid 2 dollars per day, this drives many families to send more of their members, including children, into the mines.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Kara explained to NPR that "Hundreds of thousands of people have been displaced because their villages were just bulldozed over to make place for large mining concessions.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] So you have people with no alternative, no other source of income, no livelihood.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Need for income drives families to send their children into the mines, exposing them to toxins, and potential physical health effects from falling walls.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Most families do not have a choice about sending their kids, because otherwise they would not eat.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] An increase in income would change lots of peoples lives, and likely prevent child labor.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In response to unsafe working conditions and low wages, miners and local communities in the Democratic Republic of the Congo have engaged in protests and labor activism, "driven by socioeconomic issues" (Manojlovic & Kabanga, 2023).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Miners and local communities have organized demonstrations and strikes to demand improved safety standards, fair wages, and greater corporate accountability.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These movements have also called attention to the environmental impacts of mining, including pollution and land degradation, and have sought stronger regulatory oversight.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Such activism highlights the role of affected communities in advocating for labor rights and environmental protections within the global mining industry.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In addition to public demonstrations, workers and advocacy groups have pushed for formal recognition of artisanal mining, the implementation of safety regulations, and increased oversight of mining operations.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] International organizations and civil society groups have also collaborated to promote responsible sourcing initiatives, including supply chain transparency and certification programs to reduce child labor and improve working conditions.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The details of the protests in the DRC have been harshly repressed by the police, resulting in deaths and have caused people to have been evicted from their homes (Manojlovic & Kabanga, 2023).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Through harsh conditions, people of the DRC have continued to show ongoing attempts to secure safer labor environments and more equitable participation in the benefits of resource extraction.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Included within the human rights abuses that occur during mining processes are instances of child labor.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These instances have sparked widespread criticism of mining cobalt, a mineral essential for powering modern technologies such as laptops, smartphones, and electric vehicles.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Many of these cases of child laborers are found in locations such as the Democratic Republic of Congo, South Africa, the Philippines, Australia, and Brazil.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Reports have risen of children carrying sacks of cobalt weighing 25 kg from small mines to local traders being paid for their work only in food and accommodation.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Many companies, such as Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Tesla have been implicated in lawsuits brought by families whose children were severely injured or killed during mining activities in Congo.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In December 2019, 14 Congolese families filed a lawsuit against Glencore, a mining company which supplies the essential cobalt to these multinational corporations with allegations of negligence that led to the deaths of children or injuries such as broken spines, emotional distress and forced labor.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] There have been instances of killings and evictions attributed to conflicts with mining companies.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Almost a third of 227 murders in 2020 were of Indigenous peoples rights activists on the frontlines of climate change activism linked to logging, mining, large-scale agribusiness, hydroelectric dams, and other infrastructure, according to Global Witness.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Struggles over access to land define the relationship between indigenous peoples and mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In the Democratic Republic of the Congo, there are issues with both evictions and a lack of compensation.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Sources reported widespread complicity, including allegations that government officials directly engaged in trafficking, helped facilitate the crime, and obstructed justice.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Government officials accepted bribes to overlook labor abuses, including forced labor and the worst forms of child labor, in the mining sector.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Perpetrators of sexual violence, including sex trafficking, were rarely held accountable, and security forces continued to sexually abuse and exploit victims, including children, with impunity." There is little information about what citizens of DRC are doing in retaliation.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The claimants allege severe lead poisoning caused by mining operations in Kabwe.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In Australia, the Aboriginal Bininj said mining posed a threat to their living culture and could damage sacred heritage sites.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Although Australia is one of the most profitable mining countries, "Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders (henceforward referred to as Indigenous Australians) have not shared in this bounty equitably, with social and economic disadvantage exacerbated where mining activity is the greatest.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In Brazil, more than 170 tribes organized a march to oppose controversial attempts to strip back indigenous land rights and open their territories to mining operations.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The United Nations Commission on Human Rights has called on Brazil's Supreme Court to uphold Indigenous land rights to prevent exploitation by mining groups and industrial agriculture.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] For issues such as gold mining and illegal mining, " uniform law enforcement is required to prevent the waterbed effect (when fighting miners somewhere, they pop up elsewhere); the unhinged miners have not been hinged yet.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In addition, gold trading laws need to be strengthened to ensure accountability for the illegal gold trade in the Amazon.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Uranium mining has had significant impacts on Indigenous communities because their tribes are located near their land.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In the article, *Green Victimization of Native Americans: Uranium Mining as a Form of Toxic Colonialism and Genocide*, it says, "A recent study exploring the consumption of sheep in a Navajo community demonstrated how contamination from uranium mining affected diet and had cultural implications.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Although sheep were traditionally a staple in Navajo diet, the authors found Navajo consumption of sheep was mostly ceremonial.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] However, the Navajo suggested the contamination of sheep could alter or threaten traditional ceremonies" (Fegadel, 2023).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Because of the impacts contamination from uranium mining has on the ecological system, this results in traditional tribal lifestyle to be affected.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Along with sheep, fish and local plants are used for medicinal and ceremonial purposes.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The presence of contamination in soil, water, and air pose a major risk to Native Americans.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] "In particular, the biocencentration of uranium by aquatic and terrestrial plants is a primary exposure pathway for Native Americans.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] These plants are consumed directly by Native Americans, as well as aquatic and terrestrial animals, which are then consumed by Native Americans" (Fegadel, 2023).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In *Green Victimization of Native Americans: Uranium Mining as a Form of Toxic Colonialism and Genocide*, Averi R.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Fegadel says, "The prevalence of poverty and unemployment among expendability, thus their lands are targeted by the U.S. government and large corporations.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In 1987, approximately 50% of Native Americans live in communities with one or more uncontrolled toxic waste sites" (Fegadel, 2023).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] There have already been international loopholes that threaten the safety of indigenous miners (see safety regulations).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Violence has intensified rather than fallen since U.S. conflict-mineral legislation, with statistically significant spikes in armed incidents around mine sites," which is most likely not enforced due to financial benefit.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] For justice to be secured, laws need to both encapsulate justice for indigenous communities and enforce them, despite any financial incentives to do otherwise.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] As of 2019, Mponeng is the world's second deepest mine from ground level, reaching a depth of 4 km (2.5 mi) below ground level.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The trip from the surface to the bottom of the mine takes over an hour.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] It is a gold mine in South Africa's Gauteng province.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Previously known as Western Deep Levels #1 Shaft, the underground and surface works were commissioned in 1987.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The mine is considered one of the largest gold mines in the world.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The Moab Khutsong gold mine in North West Province (South Africa) has the world's longest winding steel wire rope, which can lower workers to 3,054 metres (10,020 ft) in a single uninterrupted four-minute journey.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The deepest mine in Europe is the 16th shaft of the uranium mines in Příbram, Czech Republic, at 1,838 metres (6,030 ft).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Second is Bergwerk Saar in Saarland, Germany, at 1,750 metres (5,740 ft).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The deepest open-pit mine in the world is Bingham Canyon Mine in Bingham Canyon, Utah, United States, at over 1,200 metres (3,900 ft).
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The largest and second-deepest open-pit copper mine in the world is Chuquicamata in northern Chile, at 900 metres (3,000 ft), which annually produces 443,000 tons of copper and 20,000 tons of molybdenum.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The deepest open-pit mine with respect to sea level is Tagebau Hambach in Germany, where the base of the pit is 299 metres (981 ft) below sea level.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The largest underground mine is Kiirunavaara Mine in Kiruna, Sweden.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] With 450 kilometres (280 miles) of roads, 40 million tonnes of annually produced ore, and a depth of 1,270 metres (4,170 ft), it is also one of the most modern underground mines.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The deepest borehole in the world is Kola Superdeep Borehole at 12,262 metres (40,230 ft), but this is connected to scientific drilling, not mining.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] During the 20th century, the variety of metals used in society increased.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Today, the development of major nations such as China and India, along with technological advances, fuels an ever-greater demand.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The result is that metal mining activities are expanding, and more and more of the world's metal stocks are above ground in use rather than below ground as unused reserves.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] An example is the in-use stock of copper.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Between 1932 and 1999, copper in use in the US rose from 73 kilograms (161 lb) to 238 kilograms (525 lb) per person.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] 95% of the energy used to make aluminium from bauxite ore is saved by using recycled material.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] However, levels of metal recycling are generally low.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] In 2010, the International Resource Panel, hosted by the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), published reports on metal stocks that exist within society and their recycling rates.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] The report's authors observed that the metal stocks in society can serve as substantial anthropogenic mines above ground.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] As recycling rates are low and so much metal has already been extracted, some landfill now contain higher concentrations of metal than the mines themselves.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] This is especially true of aluminum, used in cans, and precious metals, found in discarded electronics.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] Furthermore, waste after 15 years has still not broken down, so less processing would be required when compared to mining ores.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] A study undertaken by Cranfield University has found £360 million of metals could be mined from just four landfill sites.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] There is also up to 20 MJ/kg of energy in waste, potentially making the re-extraction more profitable.
[src:mining-automation/mining-p02] However, although the first landfill mine opened in Tel Aviv, Israel in 1953, little work has followed due to the abundance of accessible ores.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In North America, where the majority of surface coal mining occurs, this method began to be used in the mid-16th century and is practiced throughout the world in the mining of many different minerals.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In North America, surface mining gained popularity throughout the 20th century, and surface mines now produce most of the coal mined in the United States.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In most forms of surface mining, heavy equipment, such as earthmovers, first remove the overburden.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Next, large machines, such as dragline excavators or bucket-wheel excavators, extract the mineral.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Advantages of surface mining include lower cost and greater safety compared to underground mining.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Disadvantages include hazards to human health and the environment.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Humans face a variety of health risks caused by mining such as different cardiovascular diseases, food, and water contamination.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Habitat destruction, alongside air, noise, and water pollution, are all significant negative environmental impacts caused by the side effects of surface mining.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] There are five main types of surface mining as detailed below.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The more common method is area stripping, which is used on fairly flat terrain, to extract deposits over a large area.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] As each long strip is excavated, the overburden is placed in the excavation produced by the previous strip.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] being extracted is at left, the removed overburden being placed at right.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Note that it is a largely flat mine for a horizontal mineral.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Open-pit mining refers to a method of extracting rock or minerals from the earth through their removal from an open pit or borrow.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] This process is done on the ground surface of the earth.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] It is best suited for accessing mostly vertical deposits of minerals.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Although open-pit mining is sometimes mistakenly referred to as "strip mining", the two methods are different (see above).
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Mountaintop removal mining (MTR) is a form of coal mining that mines coal seams beneath mountaintops by first removing the mountaintop overlying the coal seam.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Explosives are used to break up the overburden (rock layers above the seam), which is then removed.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The overburden is then dumped by haul trucks into fills in nearby hollows or valleys.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] MTR involves the mass restructuring of earth in order to reach coal seams as deep as 400 feet (120 m) below the surface.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Mountaintop removal replaces the original steep landscape with a much flatter topography.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] This method has been increasingly used in recent years in the Appalachian coal fields of West Virginia, Kentucky, Virginia, and Tennessee in the United States.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The profound changes in topography and disturbance of pre-existing ecosystems have made mountaintop removal highly controversial.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Proponents of mountaintop removal point out that once the areas are reclaimed as mandated by law, the technique provides premium flat land suitable for many uses in a region where flat land is rare.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] They also maintain that the new growth on reclaimed mountaintop mined areas is better able to support populations of game animals.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Critics contend that mountaintop removal is a disastrous practice that benefits a small number of corporations at the expense of local communities and the environment.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) environmental impact statement finds that streams near valley fills sometimes may contain higher levels of minerals in the water and decreased aquatic biodiversity.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The statement also estimates that 724 miles (1,165 km) of Appalachian streams were buried by valley fills from 1985 to 2001.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Blasting at a mountaintop removal mine expels dust and fly-rock into the air, which can then disturb or settle onto private property nearby.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] This dust may contain sulfur compounds, which some claim corrode structures and tombstones and is a health hazard.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Although MTR sites are required to be reclaimed after mining is complete, reclamation has traditionally focused on stabilizing rock and controlling erosion, but not always on reforesting the area.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Quick-growing, non-native grasses, planted to quickly provide vegetation on a site, compete with tree seedlings, and trees have difficulty establishing root systems in compacted backfill.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Consequently, biodiversity suffers in a region of the United States with numerous endemic species.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Erosion also increases, which can intensify flooding.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In the eastern United States, the Appalachian Regional Reforestation Initiative works to promote the use of trees in mining reclamation.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Dredging is a method for mining below the water table.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] It is mostly associated with gold mining.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Small dredges often use suction to bring the mined material up from the bottom of a water body.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Historical large-scale dredging operations often used a floating dredge; a barge-like vessel that scoops material up through a conveyor belt on the bow, filters out the desired component on board, and returns the unwanted material to the water via another conveyor belt on the stern.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In gravel-filled river valleys with shallow water tables, a floating dredge can work its way through the loose sediment in a pond of its own making.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Highwall mining is another form of mining sometimes conducted to recover additional coal adjacent to a surface-mined area.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The method evolved from auger mining but does not meet the definition of surface mining since it does not involve the removal of overburden to expose the coal seam.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] 2014-004 "Highwall Mining: Design Methodology, Safety, and Suitability" by Yi Luo characterizes it as a "relatively new semi-surface and semi-underground coal mining method that evolved from auger mining".
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In highwall mining, the coal seam is penetrated by a continuous miner propelled by a hydraulic pushbeam transfer mechanism (PTM).
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] A typical cycle includes sumping (launch-pushing forward) and shearing (raising and lowering the cutterhead boom to cut the entire height of the coal seam).
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] As the coal recovery cycle continues, the cutterhead is progressively launched into the coal seam for 19.72 feet (6.01 m).
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Then, the PTM automatically inserts a 19.72-foot-long (6.01 m) rectangular pushbeam (screw-conveyor segment) into the center section of the machine between the Powerhead and the cutterhead.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The pushbeam system can penetrate nearly 1,200 feet (370 m) (proven in 2015 till today) into the coal seam.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] One patented highwall mining system uses augers enclosed inside the pushbeam that prevent the mined coal from being contaminated by rock debris during the conveyance process.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Using a video imaging and/or a gamma-ray sensor and/or other geo-radar systems like a coal-rock interface detection sensor (CID), the operator can see ahead projection of the seam-rock interface and guide the continuous miner's progress.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Highwall mining can produce thousands of tons of coal in contour-strip operations with narrow benches, previously mined areas, trench mine applications, and steep-dip seams by utilizing a controlled water-inflow pump system and/or a gas (inert) venting system.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Recovery with tunneling shape of drives used by highwall miners is much better than round augering holes, but the mapping of areas that have been developed by a highwall miner are not mapped as rigorously as deep mined areas.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Very little soil is displaced in contrast with mountaintop removal; however, it is comparatively more expensive to own and operate a highwall miner.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Mapping of the outcrop, as well as core hole data and samples taken during the bench-making process, are taken into account to best project the panels that the highwall miner will cut.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Recently highwall miners have penetrated more than 1,200 feet (370 m) (2015 ongoing records into the coal seam, and today's models are capable of going farther, with the support of gyro navigation and not limited anymore by the amount of cable stored on the machine.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Historically, moving materials out of surface mines was accomplished through manual labor, horse-drawn vehicles, and/or mining railways.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Current practices tend to use haul trucks on haul roads designed into the features of the mine.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Federal governments have imposed multiple laws and regulations which mining companies have to strictly follow.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In the United States, the Surface Mining Control and Reclamation Act of 1977 mandates reclamation of surface coal mines.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Reclamation for non-coal mines is regulated by state and local laws, which may vary widely.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA), Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA), Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act (CERCLA) and many more laws deal with the subject of surface mining.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In some cases, even with proper legislation in place for surface mining some negative human health and environmental impacts remain.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Surface mining can have a number of effects on the local environment.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The negative effects involve soil, water, air, and noise pollution as well as landscape alteration and various other negatives.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] However, new technology and proper management can make it easier to properly treat the local water supply and restore the local ecology which helps rebuild the environment.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Each type of surface mining has its own environmental impact, as laid out below.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Strip mining - Once operations have ended, the tailings are placed back into the hole and covered up to make the site resemble the landscape before the mining operation.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] This process involves the removal of all ground vegetation in the area, which is a detriment to the environment.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Topsoil may be placed over the tailing along with planting trees and other vegetation.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Another reclamation method involves filling in the hole with water to create an artificial lake.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Large tailing piles left behind may contain heavy metals which can leach out acids such as lead and copper and enter into water systems.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Open-pit mining - One of the world's largest types of mine and the size of these operations leave behind massive landscape scars, destruction to environmental habitats, and substantial clean-up cost.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] An open-pit mine can yield an enormous quantity of waste rock, sinkholes can form down the road, flooding and similar negative impacts as strip mining.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Mountaintop removal mining - Involves the removal of whole mountaintops, the waste rock of which is used to flatten out the surrounding land by infilling rivers and valleys.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] This is very destructive as it physically permanently alters the landscape and the associated ecosystem.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Throughout the Appalachians in states such as Kentucky and Virginia, mountaintop removal is a common mining method where whole forests are cleared and the area becomes vulnerable to possible landslides, with restoration sometimes being too difficult/costly.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Dredging - A form of surface mining where the environmental impacts are primarily found underwater.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The method of extracting material from the seafloor or any water body leads to the harmful risk of marine life.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Overall, the effect are far less compared to the other mining methods.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] The influx of sediment can bury flora and fauna, change water levels and can alter the oxygen content.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Water and noise pollution is a concern that must be monitored because marine life is very sensitive and vulnerable to drastic and harmful changes within their ecosystem.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Highwall mining - Has a lower environmental impact than mountaintop removal because of the smaller external surface area present but there are still negative side effects.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Air and noise pollution from blasting are common environmental effects along with the large tailing piles, which can leach into waterways and numerous ecosystems.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] Properly cleaning, restoring, and removing hazards from a once operational surface mine requires a large sum of money and extensive environmental remediation.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] These remediation projects can continue on for years after the mine is closed.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In some cases, the mining companies go bankrupt leaving abandoned mines with no funding for remediation.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In other cases, mining companies are unwilling to pay for remediation, meaning litigation or regulatory action is necessary to compel the companies to commit funds to remediate.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] These legal issues often delay remediation and the environment is negatively affected.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In the United States, when the company does not exist anymore or is otherwise unable to clean the site, special taxes on hazardous waste producers (i.e. the Environmental Protection Agency Superfund) can be used to fund remediation projects.
[src:mining-automation/surface-mining] In Canada, there is a complex interaction between the evolving mining industry technologies, environmental protection legislation, and reclamation efforts.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Accessing underground ore can be achieved via a decline (ramp), inclined vertical shaft or adit.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Declines are often started from the side of the high wall of an open cut mine when the ore body is of a payable grade sufficient to support an underground mining operation, but the strip ratio has become too great to support open cast extraction methods.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] They are also often built and maintained as an emergency safety access from the underground workings and a means of moving large equipment to the workings.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Levels are excavated horizontally off the decline or shaft to access the ore body.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Stopes are then excavated perpendicular (or near perpendicular) to the level into the ore.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] There are two principal phases of underground mining: development mining and production mining.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Development mining is composed of excavation almost entirely in (non-valuable) waste rock in order to gain access to the orebody.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] To start the mining, the first step is to make the path to go down.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The path is defined as 'Decline' as describe above.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Before the start of a decline, all pre-planning of the power facility, drilling arrangement, de-watering, ventilation and, muck withdrawal facilities are required.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Production mining is further broken down into two methods, long hole and short hole.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Short hole mining is similar to development mining, except that it occurs in ore.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] There are several methods of long hole mining.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Typically, long hole mining requires two excavations within the ore at different elevations below surface (15 to 30 metres or 50 to 100 feet).
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Holes are drilled between the two excavations and loaded with explosives.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The holes are blasted, and the ore is removed from the bottom excavation.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] One of the most important aspects of underground hard rock mining is ventilation.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Ventilation is also used to manage underground temperatures for the workers.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] In deep, hot mines ventilation is used to cool the workplace; however, in very cold locations the air is heated to just above freezing before it enters the mine.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Ventilation raises are typically used to transfer ventilation from surface to the workplaces, and can be modified for use as emergency escape routes.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The primary sources of heat in underground hard rock mines are virgin rock temperature, machinery, auto compression, and fissure water.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Other small contributing factors are human body heat and blasting.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Some means of support is required in order to maintain the stability of the openings that are excavated.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] This support comes in two forms; local support and area support.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Area ground support is used to prevent major ground failure.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Holes are drilled into the back (ceiling) and walls and a long steel rod (or rock bolt) is installed to hold the ground together.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] There are three categories of rock bolt, differentiated by how they engage the host rock.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Local ground support is used to prevent smaller rocks from falling from the back and ribs.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Not all excavations require local ground support.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Using this method, mining is planned to extract rock from the stopes without filling the voids; this allows the wall rocks to cave in to the extracted stope after all the ore has been removed.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The stope is then sealed to prevent access.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Where large bulk ore bodies are to be mined at great depth, or where leaving pillars of ore is uneconomical, the open stope is filled with backfill, which can be a cement and rock mixture, a cement and sand mixture or a cement and tailings mixture.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] This method is popular as the refilled stopes provide support for the adjacent stopes, allowing total extraction of economic resources.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The mining method selected is determined by the size, shape, orientation and type of orebody to be mined.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The orebody can be narrow vein such as a gold mine in the Witwatersrand, the orebody can be massive similar to the Olympic Dam mine, South Australia, or Cadia-Ridgeway Mine, New South Wales.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The width or size of the orebody is determined by the grade as well as the distribution of the ore.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The dip of the orebody also has an influence on the mining method for example a narrow horizontal vein orebody will be mined by room and pillar or a longwall method whereas a vertical narrow vein orebody will be mined by an open stoping or cut and fill method.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Further consideration is needed for the strength of the ore as well as the surrounding rock.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] An orebody hosted in strong self-supporting rock may be mined by an open stoping method and an orebody hosted in poor rock may need to be mined by a cut and fill method where the void is continuously filled as the ore is removed.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Orebodies that do not cave readily are sometimes preconditioned by hydraulic fracturing, blasting, or by a combination of both.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Hydraulic fracturing has been applied to preconditioning strong roof rock over coal longwall panels, and to inducing caving in both coal and hard rock mines.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] In mines which use rubber-tired equipment for coarse ore removal, the ore (or "muck") is removed ("mucked out" or "bogged") from the stope using center articulated vehicles.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] These vehicles are referred to as "boggers" or LHD (Load, Haul, Dump machines).
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] These pieces of equipment may operate using diesel engines or electric motors, and resemble a low-profile front end loader.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] Electrically powered LHD utilize trailing cables which are flexible and can be extended or retracted on a reel.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] In shallower mines the ore is then dumped into a truck to be hauled to the surface.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] In deeper mines, the ore is dumped down an ore pass (a vertical or near vertical excavation) where it falls to a collection level.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] On the collection level, it may receive primary crushing by a jaw or cone crusher, or by a rockbreaker.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The ore is then moved by conveyor belts, trucks or occasionally trains to the shaft to be hoisted to the surface in buckets or skips and emptied into bins beneath the surface headframe for transport to the mill.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] In some cases the underground primary crusher feeds an inclined conveyor belt which delivers ore via an incline shaft direct to the surface.
[src:mining-automation/underground-mining-hard-rock] The ore is fed down ore passes, with mining equipment accessing the ore body via a decline from the surface.
